## Spec Format

Each spec MUST follow this exact format. The spec parser extracts "Target Agent", "Files to Modify", and "Files NOT to Modify" for pre-flight validation.

```markdown
# Spec: {agent-key} — {feature-name}

## Summary
What needs to change and why (2-3 sentences).

## Target Agent
**{agent-key}** → {Agent display name}

## Tracker Tasks
- [ ] Task 1

## Dependencies
None (or list specs that must complete first)

## Authorization Matrix
Who can do what. Required for any spec that involves auth-gated operations.

| Caller | Action 1 | Action 2 | View |
|--------|----------|----------|------|
| Role A | Yes/No   | Yes/No   | Yes  |

## Requirements
Detailed, prescriptive requirements.

### Reference Implementation
Cite specific existing files the agent should follow as patterns. Example:
- Repository pattern: `path/to/existing-repository.ts` (use constants, not string literals; no `any` casts)
- Handler pattern: `path/to/existing-handler.ts` (error types, auth checks)
- Component pattern: `path/to/existing-component.tsx` (hooks, data fetching, error handling)

### Files to Modify
- path/to/file.ts (every path MUST exist on disk or be a new file with full path)

### Files NOT to Modify
- path/to/off-limits-file.ts (owned by {other-agent})

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Criterion 1
- [ ] Criterion 2

## Pre-Flight Checklist
- [ ] All files in "Files to Modify" match the target agent's ownedPaths
- [ ] No files from another agent's boundary are listed
- [ ] If work spans multiple agents, split into separate specs (one per agent)
- [ ] Every handler/component in "Files to Modify" has a corresponding test file listed
```

